"Pathak H., Li C., Wassmann R.","Greenhouse gas emissions from Indian rice fields: Calibration and upscaling using the DNDC model",2005,"Biogeosciences","2","2",,"113","123",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-23944437986&partnerID=40&md5=7e69143865c16e3692e21ed0fff9f5e1","Unit of Simulation and Informatics, Indian Agricultural Research Institute, New Delhi, India; Institute for the Study of Earth, Oceans, and Space, University of New Hampshire, Durham, NH, United States; Institute for Meteorology and Climate Research (IMK-IFU), Forschungszentrum Karlsruhe, Garmisch-Partenkirchen, Germany; IMK-IFU, Germany","Pathak, H., Unit of Simulation and Informatics, Indian Agricultural Research Institute, New Delhi, India, IMK-IFU, Germany; Li, C., Institute for the Study of Earth, Oceans, and Space, University of New Hampshire, Durham, NH, United States; Wassmann, R., Institute for Meteorology and Climate Research (IMK-IFU), Forschungszentrum Karlsruhe, Garmisch-Partenkirchen, Germany","The Denitrification and Decomposition (DNDC) model was evaluated for its ability to simulate methane (CH4), nitrous oxide (N2O) and carbon dioxide (CO2) emissions from Indian rice fields with various management practices. The model was calibrated and validated for field experiments in New Delhi, India. The observed yield, N uptake and greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions were in good agreement with the values predicted by the model. The model was then applied for estimation of GHG emissions from rice fields in India using a newly compiled soil/climate/land use database. Continuous flooding of rice fields (42.25 million ha) resulted in annual net emissions of 1.07-1.10, 0.04-0.05 and 21.16-60.96 Tg of CH4-C, N2O-N and CO2-C, respectively, with a cumulated global warming potential (GWP) of 130.93-272.83 Tg CO2 equivalent. Intermittent flooding of rice fields reduced annual net emissions to 0.12-0.13 Tg CH4-C and 16.66-48.80 Tg CO2-C while N2O emission increased to 0.05-0.06 Tg N2O-N. The GWP, however, reduced to 91.73-211.80 Tg CO2 equivalent. The study suggested that the model could be applied for estimating the GHG emissions and the influences of agronomic management, soil and climatic parameters on the GHG emissions from rice fields in India.",,"agricultural emission; biogeochemical cycle; calibration; greenhouse gas; model; paddy field; Asia; Delhi; Eastern Hemisphere; Eurasia; India; New Delhi; South Asia; World; Oryza sativa (indica cultivar-group)",,,,,,"Adhya, T.K., Bharati, K., Mohanty, S.R., Ramakrishnan, B., Rao, V.R., Sethunathan, N., Wassmann, R., Methane emission from rice fields at Cuttack, India (2000) Nutr. Cycl. Agroecosyst., 58, pp. 95-105; Aggarwal, P.K., Kalra, N., Chander, S., Pathak, H., (2004) InfoCrop: A Generic Simulation Model for Annual Crops in Tropical Environments, p. 132. , Indian Agricultural Research Institute, New Delhi; Ahuja, D.R., Estimating regional anthropogenic emissions of greenhouse gases (1990) US-EPA Climate Change Technical Series, , Washington DC, 20; (1998) National Report on Asia Least Cost Greenhouse Gas Abatement Strategy (ALGAS), , Ministry of Environment and Forest, Government of India, New Delhi; Anastasi, C., Dowding, M., Simpson, V.J., Future CH4 emission from rice production (1992) J Geophys Res., 97, pp. 7521-7525; Aulakh, M.S., Doran, J.W., Mosier, A.R., Soil denitrification - Significance, measurement, and effects of management (1992) Adv. Soil Sci., 18, pp. 2-42; Bachelet, D., Neue, H.U., Methane emissions from wetland rice areas of Asia (1993) Chemosphere, 26, pp. 219-237; Battle, M., Bender, M., Sowers, T., Tans, P.P., Butler, J.H., Elkins, J.W., Ellis, J.T., Clarke, A.D., Atmospheric gas concentrations over the past century measured in air from fin at the south pole (1996) Nature, 383, pp. 231-235; Bhatia, A., Pathak, H., Aggarwal, P.K., Inventory of methane and nitrous oxide emissions from agricultural soils of India and their global warming potential (2004) Curr. Sci., 87 (3), p